Name: Smith, Adrian
text:
#OTD in NE History:  In 1943, on the front page of the Cozad Local, the community’s men announced they were prepared with sufficient funds to operate a “Cozad Day” at the #NorthPlatteCanteen on #FathersDay. Although, they welcomed donations of homemade birthday cakes—a “great hit” with servicemembers.

The same day, a letter appeared in the North Platte Daily Telegraph from an American soldier in the South Pacific. Identified only as a native of Omaha, the soldier had not visited the canteen but “felt he had to make a comment” after finding a feature on it titled “A Little Town with a Big Heart” in Liberty magazine.

Noting his pride in his home state, he wrote, “It makes one feel that the home front is willing to go to the limit to make life as pleasant as possible. There will be a lot of us that won’t come back, but folks like you make it truer than ever, ‘It Is Worth Fighting For.”

He closed by saying, “When the lights come, and the ships sail home in peace, I will stop for a piece of that delicious looking home-made cake.”

@SenatorFischer and I sponsor legislation to award the Congressional Gold Medal to canteen volunteers who went to the limit as they served nearly 7 million soldiers during WWII.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
In recent weeks, I’ve had conversation after conversation with constituents sounding the alarm on the same issue: robocalls and scam texts are out of control. 

So today, I delivered a communication to Attorney General Bondi demanding clear action from the Department of Justice to crack down on this growing wave of fraud. These scams are targeting our seniors, veterans, and financially vulnerable neighbors—and we need a whole-of-government response to stop them.

In my letter, I pressed DOJ to:

➡️ Detail what’s currently being done to combat fraudulent robocalls
➡️ Identify gaps in authority or resources that Congress can address
➡️ Explain how they’re coordinating with the FCC, FTC, and state leaders

This is part of a broader push I’m leading in Congress to protect consumers and hold bad actors accountable, including:

✅ The QUIET Act – to expose AI-generated robocalls and toughen penalties
✅ The STOP Scammers Act – to hit foreign scam networks where it hurts

This isn’t just about nuisance calls—it’s about protecting our people from exploitation. 

Read my full letter below. ⬇️

Name: Banks, Jim
text:
This week, @SenCortezMasto & I introduced bipartisan legislation to address excessive executive pay within the Federal Home Loan Banks System.

The Curbing Unreasonable Remuneration at Banks (CURB) Act gives @pulte, the Director of @FHFA, the authority to set reasonable compensation levels for senior executives at these institutions. 

Here’s why this matters 🧵

Name: Banks, Jim
text:
Back in April, my colleagues and I on @BankingGOP wrote to Federal Housing Finance Agency Director Bill Pulte asking for more oversight on compensation for the FHLBs.

That is why we need the CURB Act signed into law. This bipartisan legislation will enable @pulte to oversee and establish more reasonable pay amounts for these top executives.

Name: Banks, Jim
text:
As government-sponsored enterprises, FHLBs operate with public backing, which gives them an important responsibility to prioritize public interest over private gain.

However, a 2023 report from the @FHFA shows that executives earned bonuses tied to performance metrics that didn’t incentivize more housing construction and stronger communities.

In other words, the Federal Home Loan Banks’ original mission of supporting housing construction and community institutions like farms and small businesses has taken a back seat over the years.

Name: Banks, Jim
text:
.@pulte is committed towards rooting out mortgage fraud and waste at @FHFA and its regulated entities. I’m proud to stand with him and @potus when it comes to making that goal a reality. That’s why we need to pass the CURB Act.

Otherwise, the American Dream will remain out of reach for so many hard-working Hoosiers if agencies like the FHFA are tasked with only serving themselves.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Margaret Mead once said, “Never doubt that a small group of thoughtful, committed citizens can change the world.”

That spirit defines the work of the Interfaith Food Alliance—a coalition of churches, synagogues, and mosques across our community working together to fight hunger through education, advocacy, and direct service.

Yesterday, I met with leaders from the IFA and Bread for the World to discuss strengthening nutrition programs and expanding support for families in Puerto Rico—priorities I continue to lead on in Congress. I was honored to be recognized by Bread for the World as one of the top two leaders in Congress on hunger—reflecting our shared commitment to ending food insecurity.

My sincere thanks to our own Bob Anderson of Yardley and everyone at the IFA and Bread for the World for all you do for our community and our country—grateful to continue this work alongside you.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
I was happy to join @epaleezeldin to announce the proposed revision of two Biden-era energy regulations, as part of the Powering the Great American Comeback initiative—a five-pillar plan that refocuses the EPA on air and water quality, energy security, permitting reform, innovation, and global competitiveness.

This action reflects a balanced, responsible approach to deregulation that supports American energy production, protects the environment, and delivers the certainty our producers need after years of burdensome Biden-era rules that pushed investment overseas and jeopardized our path to energy dominance.

As Administrator Zeldin emphasized, even if finalized, no power plant will be allowed to emit more than it does today or did in recent years. The more energy we produce here at home, the better it is for the planet—because no nation produces energy more responsibly or with lower emissions than the United States.

Name: Durbin, Richard J.
text:
BIG NEWS. The STOP CSAM Act just advanced unanimously out of committee!

This is a momentous step toward finally holding Big Tech accountable for harm it has caused kids and families.

Big Tech’s pockets run deep, and social media companies are lobbying against any bill that would bolster accountability. Their influence is weakening.

I’m proud to have worked with Democrats and Republicans alike to highlight the failures of Big Tech and draft commonsense proposals like our STOP CSAM Act to put kids’ safety first.

This bill would finally pierce the broad immunity granted by Section 230 and open the courtroom to victims of online child sexual exploitation, as well as bolster protections and resources for survivors.

Senator Hawley and I will continue pushing for Senate passage of this bill, and I look forward to the day it becomes law.

These rules were designed to go national and force consumers, truckers, and most industries into costly electric vehicles with fewer options. It’s Community Health Improvement Week, and I’m highlighting the everyday heroes who make Western New York a healthier, more compassionate place to live.

Today, I’m proud to recognize Tyler Feliciano, Front Desk Lead at @nhcwny.

Tyler’s story is one of resilience and leadership. As a first-generation high school and college graduate, Tyler grew up helping his family navigate the complexities of healthcare. That experience drives his work at the Neighborhood Health Center, where he goes above and beyond to help patients every day.

Recently, when a patient preparing for surgery showed up with inactive insurance, Tyler didn’t miss a beat. He got her enrolled so she could still be seen, and then followed up the same day to resolve any issues before her surgery. That’s not just customer service, it’s care in action!

Thank you, Tyler, for leading with heart and showing what it truly means to serve others. Tyler represents what the City of Good Neighbors and the Neighborhood Health Center are all about.

#CHIWeek #WNY #CommunityHealth

Name: Arrington, Jodey C.

President Trump continues to deliver on his promise to cut wasteful Washington spending and get our nation’s fiscal house in order.

This $9.4 billion rescissions package is part of Republicans’ plan to right-size our bloated bureaucracy, root out woke programs, and rein-in reckless spending.

Every dollar we spend on woke and wasteful federal programs is a dollar we steal from our children’s future. We must get serious about returning to fiscal discipline and limiting the scope and scale of the federal government. It’s as much of a threat to our freedoms as it is our prosperity.

The federal government has no business subsidizing multimedia platforms and supporting the politically biased commentary of both NPR and PBS. State-sponsored media is a feature of authoritarian regimes, not free societies.

USAID has been used as a tool by Democrats and the Radical Left to advance their ridiculous and divisive DEI and Green New Deal agendas.

President Trump and House Republicans are sending a clear message: the era of a woke, wasteful, and weaponized federal government is over.

Today’s rescissions package is about stewarding tax dollars, holding bureaucrats accountable, and restoring fiscal responsibility and confidence in the People’s government.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text: 2/10 AI is moving fast. It’s already being used in medicine, law, finance and other fields where decisions carry real weight. But right now, developers and professionals are unclear on where liability sits when these systems are used. That uncertainty hurts everyone.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
🧵1/10 Today I introduced the RISE Act of 2025 — legislation to protect innovation, empower professionals, and bring real transparency to powerful AI systems.

Here’s what it does, and why it matters for America’s future. 🇺🇸🤖📷 https://t.co/9OBPnErFnY

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
4/10 Under the RISE Act, developers must publish:

-A Model Card: how the AI was trained, tested, and where it performs well or fails
-A Model Specification: what prompts & constraints shape the system's behavior. This lets doctors, lawyers, & other pros use AI safely and wisely

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
3/10 The RISE Act changes that.
It creates a safe harbor for AI developers — only if they meet clear standards for transparency and documentation.

No secrecy. No hiding the ball. Just responsible innovation.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
7/10 RISE is pro-innovation, pro-transparency, and pro-accountability. It gives AI developers a clear legal framework.

It gives professionals the tools they need to serve clients safely. And it gives America a real shot at leading in safe AI deployment.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
6/10 Good AI policy is about drawing a smart line:

- Developers have a duty to be transparent.
- Professionals have a duty to use sound judgment.
- If both do their job, innovation shouldn’t be punished when mistakes happen.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text: 5/10 In return, if a licensed professional uses the AI tool with full knowledge of its capabilities and something goes wrong, the developer is protected from civil lawsuits — as long as they acted responsibly. No protection for reckless or deceptive devs. Period.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text: 9/10 Bottom line: If we want America to lead and prosper in AI, we can’t let labs write the rules in the shadows. We need public, enforceable standards that balance innovation with trust. That’s what the RISE Act delivers. Let’s get it done.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
8/10 One more thing: RISE also protects against abuse.

- No immunity for fraud or misconduct.
- No immunity for non-professional use.

Name: Lummis, Cynthia M.
text:
10/10 Full bill text here → https://t.co/4xA5kW2fOZ

Press release → https://t.co/fXYYZT3ZLE

If you’re building or using AI in critical sectors, I want to hear from you. Let’s build a future where innovation and responsibility rise together.

Name: Waters, Maxine
text: On June 12th, 1963, one of our country’s greatest Civil Rights leaders, Medgar Evers, was assassinated in Jackson, Mississippi. Medgar was the NAACP’s first Field Secretary for Mississippi and was a tireless worker and promoter of voting rights. Medgar's death sent a shockwave through the African American community and triggered increased marches and protests against racism, segregation, and discrimination. Medgar's wife, Myrlie Evers, a civil rights leader in her own right, became a chair of the national NAACP after his death. My sincere condolences to the entire Medgar Evers family. May he rest in peace.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
I am closely watching the situation in the Middle East after Israel launched an attack on Iran’s nuclear and missile programs, and against top officials, including military leaders. 

The Trump administration has said it did not participate in the attack and has moved to protect American forces in the region. Iran would be making a serious mistake to retaliate against U.S. forces or interests. 

Iran is a malicious actor and a state sponsor of terrorism that must never be allowed to possess a nuclear weapon. 

Since the first Trump administration withdrew from the previous nuclear agreement with Iran, it has continued to enrich uranium to higher and higher levels, reducing its breakout time substantially. 

Recently, the Trump administration has attempted to negotiate a new agreement to curtail Iran’s nuclear program that looks a lot like the old agreement.

That possibility is now less probable in the wake of this attack. 

The most immediate risk at the present is that of retaliation, miscalculation, and escalation, which could spiral into a regional conflict or all out war.

After the terrible trauma of the Hamas attacks of October 7th and the war in Gaza that has followed, the last thing the world needs is a wider war. 

My heart goes out to the people of Israel, now facing dangers from every direction. I support Israel’s right to defend itself against any imminent threat, including that emanating from Iran.

It is vital that the Administration now focus on helping Israel defend itself, protect Americans who seek safety, and prevent a broader conflict so that diplomacy can resume.

It is impossible to bring about an end to conflict through endless conflict.

Name: Patronis, Jimmy
text:
🚨PRESS RELEASE🚨

Congressman Patronis Files Bill to Streamline Environmental Permits
 
WASHINGTON, D.C. – Today, Congressman Jimmy Patronis filed H.R. 3902 – Restoring Federalism in Clean Water Permitting Act aimed at cutting red tape surrounding the Section 404 permitting process, which often hampers projects that create jobs and support community priorities. This bill mandates that the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) Administrator review regulations relating to Section 404 of the Clean Water Act that allow states to assume the environmental approval processes. The goal of this review is to identify ways to reduce administrative burdens and to encourage states to manage their own permit programs. Congressman Patronis is a member of the Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure(T&I).
 
Congressman Jimmy Patronis said, “Florida is home to many rich ecosystems that attract millions of people from around the globe to visit our state. Our springs and waterways are some of the most vibrant and pristine in the world, in no small part, due to Florida’s Department of Environmental Protection and water management districts working with local, state, and federal stakeholders to keep them preserved. Many states, like Florida, have the ability to conduct environmental reviews of projects and do so in a timely manner. What we saw under the Biden Administration, however, was the Section 404 process being used to sandbag good projects. Reform is clearly needed as nearly half of states have expressed interest in assuming Section 404 and only three states have EPA-approved programs. With H.R. 3902, Congress will direct the Administrator to conduct a deep dive on the 404 processes, so important projects that aren’t harmful to the environment can get greenlighted without having to deal with bureaucratic or judicial red tape.”
 
T&I Chairman Sam Graves said, “Congressman Patronis’ bill will encourage the EPA to make important reforms to the Section 404 permit assumption process, paving the way for more states to take the lead in issuing these critical permits, which are used in a variety of infrastructure projects—from energy projects to road construction projects to water resource projects. I want to thank Congressman Patronis for his leadership on this issue by taking a critical step in restoring federalism in the Clean Water Act through common-sense reforms that empower states.”

###

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we highlight extraordinary individuals across our district working to make a difference in our community. Today, we honor a woman whose resilience and resolve have turned tragedy into a powerful force for change. Meet this week’s Hometown Hero: Jill Perez Gobora of Newtown.
 
In 2011, Jill’s sister Amy and Amy’s two young children, Molly and Gregory, were senselessly murdered in a horrific act of domestic violence. Out of that unimaginable grief, Jill made it her life’s mission to protect others from experiencing the same pain—and she has done just that.
 
In 2012, Jill, a preschool teacher at Magic Cottage in Yardley, founded Amy’s Kisses, a Bucks County-based nonprofit that has become one of our region’s most impactful grassroots organizations in the fight to end domestic violence. Its mission is twofold: to educate children early about the signs of healthy relationships and to empower students—especially those facing adversity—through educational opportunities. Since its founding, the organization has raised over $200,000 and delivered life-changing programming and resources to families, schools, and shelters throughout our community and across the country.
 
Through Amy’s Kisses’ signature program, A Bowl Full of Hearts, Jill has helped over 600 young students across 35 classrooms begin to understand what it means to build healthy, respectful relationships. The program is anchored around the children's book Jill wrote in her sister’s memory—now used in schools throughout Bucks County and beyond as a thoughtful, age-appropriate tool for teaching the building blocks of empathy, trust, and kindness. It's a simple but meaningful way to start critical conversations early and carry forward a legacy rooted in both love and prevention.
 
In addition, through the foundation, Jill awards college scholarships to students who have overcome unimaginable challenges, donates Kindle learning libraries and classroom technology to underserved schools, and partners with organizations like A Woman’s Place to ensure that children and families have the resources they need to stay safe, heal, and thrive.
 
As the author of Kayden’s Law and a proud champion of the bipartisan reauthorization of the Violence Against Women Act, I’ve worked in Congress to strengthen protections for survivors and ensure that the safety of children is never an afterthought. But lasting change requires a united effort. It means partnering with local leaders and advocates like Jill, whose work is making an impact where it matters most: in classrooms, homes, and communities. Together, we are advancing a shared mission—to prevent violence before it starts, to protect the vulnerable, and to build a future where every child grows up safe, supported, and seen.
 
Jill is not just carrying on her sister’s legacy, she’s building her own—one that is changing how we educate, protect, and respond to domestic violence. She is making our community stronger, smarter, and safer.
 
Jill, thank you for your courage, leadership, and commitment to our shared mission. We are proud to stand with you, and honor you as this week’s Hometown Hero.

Name: Bilirakis, Gus M.
text:
Synthetic opioids, such as fentanyl, lead to nearly 70% of all overdose deaths, as the drug can be deadly in even small doses and is up to 50 times stronger than heroin and 100 times stronger than morphine. In 2022, more than 200 people died from fentanyl and opioid-related overdoses each day – making fentanyl the leading cause of death for Americans under 50 years old.  Fentanyl claims more lives than heart disease, cancer, suicide, and homicide.  If the temporary order scheduling fentanyl related substances (FRS) ends, several FRS will become street-legal, law enforcement will lose authority to seize them, and drug traffickers will continue to funnel increasingly deadly drugs into the United States.  

This week, I proudly voted in support of the HALT Fentanyl Act, which permanently classifies fentanyl-related substances (FRS) in Schedule I of the Controlled Substances Act.  It also ensure law enforcement has the resources needed to keep these drugs off the street and allows for further research of FRS.  We are doing everything in our power to stop fentanyl from claiming more American lives – everyone should support our efforts to halt this deadly crisis.  The measure now heads to the President’s desk to be signed into law.

Name: LaMalfa, Doug
text:
President Trump signed a new Executive Order to overhaul how we prevent and respond to wildfires, and I was glad to be at the White House as he signed it.

This order cuts through the bureaucracy, strengthens coordination between federal and local fire programs, and makes sure our firefighters have the tools they need to act quickly and effectively. It also clears the way for better land management, faster use of prescribed burns and fire retardants, and puts unused military aircraft to work in wildfire response.

This is a big step toward preventing the kind of out-of-control wildfires we’ve seen in recent years, and I look forward to seeing it put into action.

Name: Booker, Cory A.
text:
The conditions at the Delaney Hall ICE detention facility in Newark are untenable. With serious security lapses, numerous reports of mistreatment by staff of detainees, complaints of persistent food shortages, and a troubling lack of transparency from facility administrators, it’s clear that GEO Group has shown it cannot—or will not—operate Delaney Hall humanely or safely. I have long opposed privately owned and operated immigration detention facilities because they are mired by rampant abuse and neglect of those in their care. 

After spending millions of dollars in upgrades it continues to be a house of horrors. The consequences of GEO’s mismanagement, and the Department of Homeland Security’s resistance to Congressional oversight, are borne by my neighbors in Newark and those detained at Delaney Hall. The Department of Homeland Security has a duty to work with Congress to address the problem, take immediate action to improve the conditions at Delaney Hall, and ensure the proper and fair treatment of those detained.

Name: Brecheen, Josh
text:
Yesterday, we voted to pass the first White House rescissions package: a necessary (first step) action to defend American taxpayers from decades of unconstitutional and irresponsible government spending allowed by both parties in Washington. 

While this package does not address every area of government spending, it cuts $9.4 billion in wasteful, woke, and weaponized programs that have long burdened Americans. 

For example, the package claws back $8.3 billion from USAID for line items like $9.3 million to teach Russian doctors to perform abortions, $1 million to Haiti for voter ID, and $833,000 to support “transgender sex workers” in Nepal. It also targets funding for programs that have served as vehicles for leftist agendas at the taxpayer’s expense, including NPR and PBS.

These shameful priorities do not serve the American people. Taxpayer money should never subsidize ideology, whether at home or abroad. We must continue to redirect all government funding to core national interests, not insidious globalist projects. 

When I ran for office, it was on the platform to get us back to Constitutional adherence, including the fiscal realm. The cuts in today’s rescissions package stem from priorities that were never laid out within the eighteen enumerated powers of the Constitution. Such expenditures are an abusive overreach of government power and force a bloated bureaucracy into American lives. This is not the role the Founders intended the government to play and passing these cuts begins to restore that truth.

This vote was a part of a broader effort to address our $36 trillion national debt and the inflation hurting Americans. While every cut counts, there is much more to be done, and I look forward to swiftly passing every rescissions package the White House sends to Congress.

The news yesterday was insane. So much happened.

But what didn’t really get covered was one of the cruelest bills to ever pass the House.

6 ways that this bill will hurt, if not kill, children and families. 🧵🎥👇🏼

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
It makes permanent about $10 billion in DOGE cuts.

These are cuts that Elon Musk, Donald Trump and others in the administration, the billionaires, want.

This bill is a legitimate example of how billionaires are running the government. The world's richest people are going after the country’s and the world’s poorest children.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
1. The bill slashes $4.15 billion in humanitarian programs for children.

Globally, this means that 40 million children will no longer have school.

Hunger will spread and at least 3.6 million children will go without clean water.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 2. Another $800 million in permanent cuts to children and families fleeing violence.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 5. Over $435 million cut to programs that provide medicine, vaccines and other support to children all over the world.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
3. A $300 million cut to family planning services.

48 million people will be affected and it could lead to 34,000 maternal deaths.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
4. They’re permanently cutting $400 million from one of the most successful HIV/AIDs programs ever.

This program has saved over 25 million lives.

8 million babies were born HIV free because of this program.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: 6. They’re cutting PBS – Sesame Street – meaning kids here will go without the early learning and other educational programming that PBS provides.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text: It barely had the votes in the House. Hopefully the Senate will kill this bill.

Name: Landsman, Greg
text:
Not only will this hurt children and families, some of whom will die….this undermines our role in the world. This makes the world and us less safe.

When we leave and abandon these places and people, one of our adversaries will fill the void.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: Tariff-driven inflation hasn’t materialized. Why? Let’s examine some key factors in this THREAD: 1/🧵

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 2/ China has massive processing and manufacturing overcapacity across the board. They do this to drive out competition and achieve control over a given sector. They drop prices to rock bottom with the intention of becoming the only global supplier of a product or industry process.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 3/ This drives margins so low that these producers often operate at a loss, but they remain competitive because of support from government subsidies.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 4/ HOWEVER, when we levy a massive tariff on China, the jigg is up! They can’t subsidize industry at the level necessary to remain competitive and the supply chains snap back to a more market-driven orientation, allowing the U.S. and our allies to compete on a more level playing field again.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 6/ In addition to continued automation and AI integration, downward trajectories on consumption due to collapsing populations in East Asia and China have offset industrialization-driven demand and naturally offset inflation pressure.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 5/ Over-levered with extraordinary corporate debt and “shadow financing” and compounded by this dramatically underutilized capacity, China must then drastically lower their prices to offset tariff impacts in order to compete with lower tariff jurisdictions. It’s either that or an economic crunch.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 7/ In a perfect vacuum, tariffs would likely result in a one-time bump in inflation, but we don’t live in a vacuum. Businesses in most nations want to be producers and will fulfill that production at competitive prices. As a result, tariffs as constructed have thus far resulted in lower inflation and unparalleled domestic investment.

Name: Begich, Nicholas J.
text: 8/ Free trade requires fair trade, and fair trade requires a level playing field. America First Works.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
I’m proud to be the first member of Congress to complete and graduate from the U.S. @NavalWarCollege’s Master’s Program in Defense and Strategic Studies after more than three years of coursework.

I was honored to receive my diploma from Naval War College President Rear Admiral Darryl Walker and to be joined by @SECNAV John C. Phelan for this special occasion. Secretary Phelan delivered the commencement address and gave a powerful speech that captured the spirit of service and leadership that defines our armed forces.

I'm especially grateful to have my wife Imelda and our daughters Christina and Catherine by my side to celebrate this milestone.

This degree strengthens my work on the Defense, Military Construction and Veterans Affairs, and Homeland Security Appropriations Subcommittees, where I fight every day to ensure our servicemembers, veterans, and first responders have the support they've earned. The courage and commitment of the men and women in uniform who serve our country continue to inspire me every day.

I’d like to offer my sincere thanks to the U.S. Naval War College, its administrators, and its world-class educators for their dedication to training military leaders from the United States and allied nations around the world.

Education is one of the greatest investments we can make – in ourselves, in our service, and in the future of this country.

Name: Luján, Ben Ray
text:
Iran should never have a nuclear weapon – and its nuclear ambitions remain one of the greatest threats to Israel, the region, and global security. This conflict must be de-escalated before it spirals further out of control.
 
Israel has a right to defend itself. However, Netanyahu’s decision to strike just before U.S. nuclear talks is deeply concerning and a clear signal of how little respect global leaders have for President Trump’s leadership. His administration has abandoned strategy and replaced coalition-building with isolation – weakening the very alliances that keep us safe.
 
The U.S. must act immediately to reassert diplomatic leadership, prevent a broader war, and stop Iran’s nuclear development before it’s too late. Nothing is more important than keeping Americans and our allies safe.

This agreement paused decades of litigation and charted a desperately needed path forward for the Columbia River Basin. The Trump Administration’s reckless decision today sets the Pacific Northwest back tremendously and undermines our relationship with Tribal nations.  
 
Now, we must find a new path forward that ensures a future for the salmon, expands our reliable clean energy grid, and protects the irreplaceable environment of the Pacific Northwest.

Name: Friedman, Laura
text:
I am monitoring the situation following Israel’s targeted strike on Iranian military and nuclear sites, and Iran’s retaliatory assault. 

There is no question that Iran’s pursuit of nuclear weapons and its destabilizing regional behavior, including its direct sponsorship of terrorist activities across the world, pose a serious threat to U.S. interests, Israel, and our allies in the region. In the last few days, international nuclear regulators have determined that Iran was in violation of its nonproliferation obligations and possibly moving closer to producing nuclear weapons.  For the sake of international stability, this Iranian regime must never acquire a nuclear weapon. 

As we move forward, we must prioritize diplomatic efforts to prevent broader conflict. The United States must help foster deescalation and diplomacy, for the sake of all the people of the region.

Name: Meuser, Daniel
text:
The “No Kings” protests are being framed as anti-Trump, but they are, in truth, anti-American. These protests are deliberately timed to counter a day when we celebrate our nation’s Flag and honor the creation of the U.S. Army—a force that has defended freedom not only here at home, but around the world. That alone speaks volumes.

Let’s be clear about what this movement represents: an agenda rooted in a vision of big government, federal control, and contempt for the values that built this country. They oppose school choice. They sneer at capitalism and free markets. They want more spending, more federal employees, and more IRS agents—80,000 of them. Their party pushed H.R. 1, a federal takeover of our elections. They treat the Constitution not as the rulebook that created the greatest nation on Earth, but as a document they can alter when it suits them.

The Left believes in the government. We believe in the people. They push central control. We champion limited government and individual freedom.

As we celebrate the birth of the United States Army—an institution that secured liberty for our country, for Europe, and for our allies—let’s also reject this cynical attempt to undermine America’s founding values. The Declaration of Independence was the “why.” The Constitution is the “how.” And we intend to defend both.

Name: Womack, Steve

Name: Collins, Susan M.
text:
Today, we celebrate the 250th birthday of the United States Army. For two and a half centuries, the Army has defended our nation, responded in times of crisis, and upheld the cause of freedom.

Its legacy is defined not only by battlefield victories, but by the strength, discipline, and courage of the men and women who have proudly worn the uniform.

One of them was my father, Donald Collins, who served as an infantry sergeant in World War II. He was wounded twice and earned two Purple Hearts and a Bronze Star for his service during the Battle of the Bulge. I recently traveled with a bipartisan Senate delegation to Belgium and Luxembourg to honor those who fought in that pivotal campaign 80 years ago, and to reflect on the extraordinary sacrifices made by our Greatest Generation.

From the Revolutionary War to the Civil War, World War I, World War II, and all other conflicts where the U.S. Army has been called upon, soldiers have stood ready to serve, and the people of our nation are forever grateful.

In a democracy, we do not respond to acts of public policy with acts of violence motivated by extremism.

In the midst of this conflict, I am urging the Trump Administration to protect American citizens, troops, and diplomats, and to help Israel defend itself against Iranian attacks. The Trump Administration must engage in effective deterrence and diplomacy to prevent this conflict from spiraling wider and dragging the United States into war.

If you are traveling in the Middle East, I want to be sure that you are staying safe and getting security alerts. Please stay up to date on the State Department’s Security Alerts here: https://t.co/OIRh5F8fb2.

And they want you to blame immigrants, trans people, or anyone who doesn’t look like you, pray like you, or love like you.

Name: Cole, Tom
text:
On this Father’s Day, I can’t help but reflect and be thankful for my own father, John Cole.

My late father lived a dutiful life, dedicating everything to not only our family, but also our country. He spent twenty years in the Air Force, making exponential sacrifices every single day for this nation, and then worked an additional two decades as a civilian federal employee at Tinker Air Force Base in Oklahoma.

Growing up, and still today, I greatly admired my dad’s service. He was truly a hero. He joined the Army Air Corps on the eve of World War II and by the time he left the military, he was the second most senior master sergeant in the Air Force. My father was known throughout the USAF as the one of the best to run a crew to maintenance airplanes. In fact, he won the “Dock of the Month” prize so many times that McGuire Air Force Base stopped giving the prize out as a whole. Then, when he was placed at Dover Air Force Base, he was assigned the worst dock. Yet, without surprise, he still managed to win the same award seven times at Dover – a testament to his impressive mechanic skills.

Unfortunately, during the last several years of his life, my father battled Alzheimer’s disease. My mother, brother, and I watched him helplessly and with heavy hearts as he became a different person and slowly lost a lifetime of memories throughout the various stages of the disease. He fought the disease with all his strength, but he sadly lost the battle. Yet, the lessons my dad taught me still live on in my heart. I got my strong work ethic from him and am thankful every day that I had a father worth missing so much.

So, as we all celebrate our fathers today, let us remember to thank them for the examples they have set, the love they have shown, and the legacies they have left behind. Happy Father’s Day everyone!

Envié una carta al Departamento de Seguridad Nacional (DHS, por sus siglas en inglés) expresando serias preocupaciones sobre la reciente detención de Gregory Sanabria, un valiente preso político que pasó más de tres años encarcelado—incluyendo en el infame centro de tortura de Maduro, El Helicoide. Durante ese tiempo, estuvo al borde de la muerte. Si es devuelto al régimen de Maduro, su vida estaría en grave peligro.

Me preocupa cada vez más el creciente número de casos en Estados Unidos de personas que han huido de regímenes opresivos y están siendo detenidas con miras a una posible deportación. Casos como el de Sanabria, y muchos otros con reclamos legítimos de persecución, requieren una revisión exhaustiva.

Sanabria no debe ser devuelto a sus opresores. Estados Unidos debe seguir siendo un faro de la libertad y la democracia—porque cuando protegemos a quienes huyen de la tiranía, demostramos la excepcionalidad estadounidense, reafirmamos nuestro liderazgo y fortalecemos nuestra seguridad nacional frente a las amenazas de narco-dictaduras criminales y antiamericanas como la del régimen venezolano.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
I sent a letter to DHS raising serious concerns about its recent detainment of Gregory Sanabria, a brave political prisoner who spent more than three years imprisoned—including in Maduro’s infamous torture center, El Helicoide. During that time, he was nearly killed. If returned to the Maduro regime, his life would be in grave danger.

I’m increasingly concerned with the growing cases of people in the United States who have fled oppressive regimes and are being detained and held for possible deportation. Cases like Sanabria’s, and so many others with legitimate claims of persecution, require a thorough review.

Sanabria must not be returned to his oppressors. The United States must continue to be a beacon of freedom and democracy–because when we protect those fleeing tyranny, we demonstrate American exceptionalism, uphold our leadership, and strengthen our national security in the face of threats from anti-American criminal narco-dictatorships like the one in Venezuela.

Name: Davis, Donald G.
text:
Anyone requiring emergency, primary, or secondary healthcare services deserves access to timely, affordable, and qualified providers prepared to meet them where they are. To that end, we are cosponsoring three bipartisan bills that will improve delivery of care:

▪️H.R. 2936, the Addressing Boarding and Crowding in the Emergency Department (ABC-ED) Act, a bipartisan bill to leverage existing CDC resources, without requiring new funding, to pilot data-driven solutions that aim to reduce ED boarding and improve patient flow and safety.

▪️H.R. 3791, the EMS Counts Act, legislation to require the Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS) to revise the Standard Occupational Classification System to accurately reflect the number of paramedics, EMTs, and other first responders throughout communities nationwide.

▪️H.R. 3747, the Accelerating Access to Dementia & Alzheimer’s Provider Training (AADAPT) Act, a bill delivering specialized training directly to frontline health care providers, by ensuring that individuals and families facing an Alzheimer’s diagnosis receive earlier support, more accurate information, and care that reflects their personal needs.

By 2036, the U.S. is projected to face a shortfall of up to 86,000 physicians—a crisis that threatens access to care in every corner of the country.

That’s why I introduced the Resident Physician Shortage Reduction Act—a bipartisan plan to strengthen our health care workforce and meet rising demand:

✅ Adds 14,000 new Medicare-funded residency slots over 7 years
✅ Prioritizes rural, underserved, and high-need communities
✅ Supports hospitals training above capacity
✅ Invests in rural pipelines and physician diversity

This bill strengthens our physician workforce—ensuring more doctors, better access, and a health care system that meets the needs of every patient.

Name: Scott, Rick
text:
I believe Medicaid is a critical safety net for those who truly need it. I grew up before Medicaid existed, and when my brother was diagnosed with a bone disease, my parents couldn’t find a doctor that we could afford. My mother drove hours just to get him care at a charity hospital. Medicaid is intended to support people like my brother so no family has to go through what we did.

We now have the opportunity with the Big Beautiful Bill to ensure Medicaid is returned to its original purpose and that these dollars support our most vulnerable. This means stopping blue states, like California and New York, from gaming the system so they can use American tax dollars to give illegal aliens free health care.

Name: Kean, Thomas H.
text:
This week's #NJ07 Law Enforcement Hometown Hero is Officer Alex DiCairano of the @HackettstownPD.
 
In the span of just a few months, Officer DiCairano responded to two life-threatening emergencies with extraordinary courage. In April 2024, he performed CPR and used an AED to revive a cardiac arrest victim, for which he received the Lifesaving Award. Then in June, he bravely responded to an active shooter incident, risking his own life to help secure the scene and rescue a victim—an act of heroism that has earned him the Medal of Honor.
 
Officer DiCairano, thank you for your selfless service, quick action, and unwavering dedication to the Hackettstown community.

text: The increasingly aggressive and undemocratic actions by the Trump Administration are what you would expect of Russia or another authoritarian country. It's un-American. This month, I’ve stood with my colleagues to call out these disgraceful acts and demand accountability.

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
As Trump deploys ICE to carry out his cruel, inhumane deportation agenda, I want immigrant communities to know that I see you & I’m doing everything I can to fight for you.

As a Member of Congress, here’s what I can do when it comes to ICE 🧵

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text: 🔗 You can learn your rights and download information to share with friends at https://t.co/Q9aBg2cayx

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
📚One of the biggest things we can do is share Know Your Rights information.

My team and I have partnered with local law firms to host KYR info sessions, town halls, and distribute KYR pamphlets in multiple languages so folks can be prepared if ICE comes to their door.

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
We can also assist you with casework. My team can advocate on your behalf to federal agencies about

➡️Immigrant Visa Applications
➡️Non-Immigrant Visa Applications
➡️Asylum Cases
➡️Employment Authorization
➡️DACA and TPS Cases
➡️Citizenship, naturalization, and oath ceremonies

You can get help from our office at https://t.co/rhpDGkrPYZ

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
📝As a Member of Congress, I can also work to hold federal agencies accountable and conduct oversight.

After ICE arrested people at PHX immigration courts, I wrote a letter to DHS demanding answers about ICE’s conduct: https://t.co/zMdYcoYWDr

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text: I also conducted a surprise visit to the Eloy Detention Center and spoke with many women about how they were wrongly detained, and the horrible conditions they now face. Sharing their stories is one of our most powerful tools in this moment.

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text: As ICE is increasing their presence in Phoenix, my team is working with local organizations on the ground to monitor the situation, observe ICE activity, and advocate for constituents who have been detained.

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
Unfortunately, as a federal elected official, there are also things we are legally prohibited from doing.

We cannot

❌Post or share live information about impending ICE raids
❌Provide legal advice
❌Direct people to specific law firms or organizations

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
We are also so grateful to our community for showing up for each other.

If you are a community bystander who is observing ICE activity, there are a few things for you to remember 👇

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
➡️ Do not interfere with federal agents, and do not lie or mislead.
➡️ You can record enforcement actions, but do not share while they are ongoing.
➡️ You can loudly vocalize legal guidance, including Know Your Rights info

Name: Ansari, Yassamin
text:
To our immigrant communities, I will always stand with you and fight for you.

As your voice in Congress, I’m doing everything I can to push back against Trump’s authoritarian overreach and make sure our communities are protected.

🧵We have a Big Beautiful Opportunity to reduce reckless spending in Washington.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
1️⃣Saving Billions in Bogus Payments
 
Last year, more than $160 billion in fraudulent and improper payments occurred because bureaucrats are asleep at the wheel and spending lacks proper oversight.
 
Barbie dolls, gangsters, and even kids got in on the fun at taxpayers' expense.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
2️⃣Ending Unemployment for the Idle Rich
 
Thousands earning MORE than one million dollars a year received over $271 million in unemployment insurance during the first two years of the Biden admin, paid for by the taxes of hardworking Americans and small businesses.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
We can bring this number down to $0 with my DOGE in Spending Act.
 
My bill with @RepAaronBean makes permanent a key Trump Executive Order to create a rigorous process to safeguard tax dollars and effectively eliminate improper payments.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
My Ending Unemployment Payments to Jobless Millionaires Act will disqualify anyone making a million dollars or more from being eligible for unemployment income support.
 
Our nation’s safety net shouldn’t be strained by subsidizing the lifestyles of the self-sufficient.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
3️⃣Eliminating Welfare for Politicians
 
With former presidents securing pricey speeches, book arrangements, and even Netflix deals, taxpayers do not need to provide extravagant benefits.
 
Even worse, tax dollars are currently used to fund presidential campaigns!

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
My Presidential Allowance Modernization Act will curb cushy perks for ex-presidents and my ELECT Act will eliminate the Presidential Election Campaign Fund that utilizes tax dollars to fund political campaigns.

These proposals have the potential to save hundreds of millions of dollars.

Name: Ernst, Joni
text:
My bill to count EVERY error, require states to recollect overpayments, and force states to pay back what they owe, could save $91 billion over the next decade.
 
Tracking errors and recouping overpayments is common sense and will save big bucks.

text:
4️⃣SNAP Back Overpayments
 
Taxpayers lose nearly a billion dollars *each month* to SNAP overpayments — yet countless errors are hidden because anything under $56 isn’t even reported.
 
That needs to change.

My Protecting Taxpayers’ Wallet Act with @RepScottPerry ends the practice of taxpayer-funded union time and requires federal unions to reimburse taxpayers for ALL costs from union-related activities.
 
Bureaucrats get paid to serve the American people, not themselves!

The absurd policy of taxpayer-funded union time allows federal employees to engage in union activities when they are supposed to be serving the American people.

Name: Gallego, Ruben
text:
There’s a lot going on in DC right now. But I want to sound the alarm on an issue that Republicans want you to forget: They’re trying to pass a budget that will strip health care away from millions of Americans to fund tax cuts for the ultra-wealthy. And if you think you’re paying too much to go to the doctor right now, it’s about to get worse. This comes at a time when costs are already too high, especially with Trump’s reckless tariffs.

Congressional Republicans are trying to ram through congress a budget bill that will make drastic cuts to Medicaid in U.S. history. If House Republicans get their way, more than 300,000 Arizonans will lose their health care, including 200,000 people on Medicaid and over 100,000 more who get their plan through the marketplace. On top of that, these cuts would force rural nursing homes and hospitals to close, push more people into overcrowded ERs, and cause over 1,000 avoidable deaths each year.

The Senate is currently negotiating their version of the budget plan, and even some Republican members know that these cuts would be political suicide. But the GOP’s top priority is keeping Donald Trump happy, and so they are charging ahead anyway with throwing working Americans under the bus.

These cuts will hit hardworking families, seniors, children, people with disabilities, and rural communities the hardest.

In the past few months, I’ve held town halls across Arizona to hear from families how much of a lifeline Medicaid is for them.

Here are just some of the stories I heard:

“I am begging you to advocate for Medicaid, especially for people like my son Parker, who is a child with multiple disabilities. Parker would not be alive today if it worked for Medicaid and all of the services that it provides children like him. Our family would not be able to sustain financially if we didn't have access to the services that it provides with therapies and medical interventions.” – Bridget in Phoenix

“I qualify for Medicare due to the rare disease I live with, in the beginning of the disease I was on Medicare before transitioning to Medicare. I live with Reflex Sympathetic Dystrophy (RSD), which requires ongoing treatments and medications to manage debilitating pain and maintain basic functionality. If I lost Medicare benefits, I would face impossible choices daily—skipping critical care, rationing meds, and plunging into financial ruin just to survive.” – Barbie in Phoenix

“My daughter was born in 2005 with a rare genetic condition that has resulted in many complex and life limiting medical conditions, along with significant cognitive and physical disabilities. She requires full care and assistance for every daily activity like dressing, bathing, feeding, etc. [...] I am a widow and an only parent to her. I have to work to provide a roof over our head and to try and give her a life she is deserving of, but I can't do it without the support and services provided by Medicaid.” – Dawn in Chandler

Bridget. Parker. Barbie. Dawn.

That’s who we’re fighting for.

Republicans are fighting for someone else. While their plan takes health coverage away from the people who need it most, it would give households making over $1 million a year an average tax break of $62,000.

This isn’t about reducing the deficit or cutting waste, it’s about rigging the system for the ultra-rich while hardworking everyday families pay the price.

I won’t let that happen.

I’m going to fight like hell to stop this bill and protect the health care that millions of Arizonans count on every single day.

Name: Diaz-Balart, Mario
text:
It was a pleasure to meet with Steve Kirk, President of Rural Neighborhoods, as well as Commissioner Burt L. Saunders, and to see the progress of the Golden Gate Affordable and Workforce Housing Project, which is currently under construction. Once completed, the development will offer 350 affordable housing units, supporting the needs of seniors, veterans, and essential service personnel, including healthcare workers, educators, and first responders.
 
Through my work on the House Appropriations Committee, I’m proud to have aided in this effort by successfully securing $2 million in funding for the Golden Gate Affordable and Workforce Housing Project in 2023.
 
Thank you to Steve Kirk and the Rural Neighborhoods team for your vision, advocacy, and determination in bringing this project to fruition.

I remain committed to prioritizing housing programs that serve our most vulnerable populations and South Florida, and will continue working with dedicated community partners, including Rural Neighborhoods.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
With public confidence in air travel shaken, we have a responsibility to act—not delay.

I sent a letter to Secretary Duffy urging the FAA to enforce the Saracini Aviation Safety Act—the bipartisan law I authored to require secondary cockpit barriers on all newly manufactured passenger aircraft.

This law was designed to prevent another 9/11. Airlines have had over two decades to prepare, and any attempt to delay implementation is not just unacceptable—it’s dangerous.

We didn’t fight to make this law a reality just to see it pushed aside.

Since coming to Congress, I’ve worked to secure our skies, support our flight crews, and improve the traveler experience. That mission continues, and I will not back down.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
My Laredo Outreach Coordinator, Melissa Peña, joined city leaders, transit officials, and community members to celebrate a major milestone for public transportation in our city made possible by federal dollars I helped secure: the expansion of El Metro Transit’s fleet, the largest in Laredo’s history.

This achievement was driven by federal funding from the U.S. Department of Transportation’s Federal Transit Administration, including $7.4 million from the Low or No Emission Bus Program and $4.4 million from the Urbanized Area Formula Grants. With these federal funds and local matching support, El Metro has added 19 brand new compressed natural gas buses to its fleet, significantly expanding access to clean, reliable transportation for our community.

As a senior member of the House Appropriations Committee, I remain committed to fighting for federal dollars to support infrastructure projects that improve quality of life in South Texas.

With more reliable routes, improved air quality, and expanded service for seniors, students, workers, and families, El Metro is helping connect our residents to jobs, education, healthcare, and opportunity. Public transportation is more than just a ride, it is a lifeline.

I thank Mayor Dr. Victor Treviño, @officialcityoflaredo, @metro_transit, and all our local partners for their leadership in delivering a modern, sustainable, and accessible transit system for the people of Laredo. I am especially grateful to the El Metro drivers, maintenance workers, General Manager Robert Garza, and Assistant General Manager Monica Garcia. Their dedication keeps our city moving every day. Together, we are building a stronger, more connected community.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
🚨HISTORIC BRIDGE EXPANSION WIN FOR LAREDO🚨

President @realDonaldTrump has officially approved the Colombia Solidarity Bridge expansion - the latest in a series of major bridge projects unlocking cross-border trade for our region.

This brings the total to five international bridge projects in Laredo that now hold presidential permits. That’s the most ever approved for a single region on the U.S.-Mexico border. These projects include:

✅ The World Trade Bridge expansion.
✅ The Colombia Solidarity Bridge expansion.
✅ The Green Corridors Intelligent Freight Transportation System.
✅ The Laredo 4/5 International Bridge.
✅ The Kansas City Southern International Bridge.

The World Trade Bridge is now the most active land port in the United States. The Colombia Solidarity Bridge ranks as the third busiest in the southwest U.S.

Laredo is already the ninth largest port in the world and this expansion will help us meet rising demand, ease congestion, and supercharge trade.

The Colombia expansion includes new southbound and northbound commercial bridge spans, allowing the existing bridge to handle FAST commercial vehicles and oversized traffic. It will also create dedicated lanes for non-commercial vehicles and buses, streamlining traffic flow and modernizing one of the most critical ports on the U.S.-Mexico border.

This is part of a broader effort to position the Port of Laredo to accommodate the growing volume of U.S.-Mexico trade, which surpassed $300 billion in 2023.

I’d like to extend my special thanks to @SenTedCruz and @JohnCornyn for their partnership and to @realDonaldTrump for delivering this latest permit and helping keep Laredo at the heart of the American economy.

Laredo doesn’t just move freight: we move America.

If President Trump wanted to take military action, he would’ve done so already. I’m seeing many people speculate as to what’s happening behind closed doors, but the fact is, the circle is very small and not many people know what is happening other than the President‘s team and a select few. 

He has been right on many occasions and thus far has made the best decisions regarding the pursuit of peace, encouraging peace talks, as well as putting Americans first and keeping our service members safe. 

Right now, everyone needs to pray. Pray for our people. Our nation. For the civilians in Israel AND the civilians in Iran. War is NEVER a good thing. Our president has the weight of the world on his shoulders and right now he needs our support and prayer.

Do not read into the posts from Senators or members of the House speculating at what Trump will do.  They do not know what’s going on. Beware of disinformation campaigns as well.

text:
Few Presidents have had to confront the incredibly difficult set of decisions now before President Trump. 

Help Israel? Help how? Allow Iran to reconstitute its nuclear program if Israel can’t finish the job with its own arsenal?

The President is right- Iran, a country whose motto is “Death to America”cannot be allowed to have a nuclear weapon. Full stop. That is peace through strength. That is America First.

President Trump is doing EXACTLY what he should be doing: stating a clear red line (and a very reasonable one), and leaving all options on the table to deal with it.

No, none of this means we get dragged into a war. That is highly simplistic thinking. There are lots of options in between doing nothing and literally sending in the Marines. 

Let’s not forget, Trump’s first presidency was marked by maximum pressure on Iran–he ordered the strike on Soleimani, Iran’s chief exporter of terror–all while not leading us into a war with Iran.  

Let the President do his job and let’s back him up.

Name: Hinson, Ashley
text:
Since taking office, President Trump has secured an unprecedented amount of economic investment for American businesses and taxpayers—setting the stage for a new era of prosperity. The announcements keep coming, and it’s further proof that President Trump’s economic agenda is working. In recent months:

​​- John Deere announced plans to invest $20 billion in the US over the next 10 years, including in Waterloo, Iowa.
- Apple announced a $500 billion investment in U.S. manufacturing and training.
- IBM announced a $150 billion investment over the next five years in its U.S.-based growth and manufacturing operations.
- Project Stargate, led by Japan-based Softbank and U.S.-based OpenAI and Oracle, announced a $500 billion private investment in U.S.-based artificial intelligence infrastructure.
- Cyclic Materials, a Canadian advanced recycling company for rare earth elements, announced a $20 million investment in its first U.S.-based commercial facility, located in Mesa, Arizona.
- Taiwan Semiconductor Manufacturing Company (TSMC) announced a $100 billion investment in U.S.-based chips manufacturing.
- NVIDIA, a global chipmaking giant, announced it will invest $500 billion in U.S.-based AI infrastructure over the next four years amid its pledge to manufacture AI supercomputers entirely in the U.S. for the first time.
- GE Aerospace announced a $1 billion investment in manufacturing across 16 states — creating 5,000 new jobs.
- Cra-Z-Art, the biggest toymaker in the U.S., said it will move a “large percentage” of its China-based manufacturing back home.
- Amsterdam-based AMG Critical Minerals announced a $15 million investment to build a chrome manufacturing facility in Pennsylvania.

This means more investment, more jobs, and more money in Iowans’ and Americans’ pockets.

As someone who’s been on the wrong end of bad U.S. intelligence in combat, I’m one of the most skeptical voices in Congress when it comes to trusting the intel community.

They enriched uranium beyond civilian levels, violated international agreements, and ignored repeated IAEA (International Atomic Energy Agency) warnings. This wasn’t speculation—it was a calculated sprint toward nuclear capability by a regime that chants “Death to America.”

President Trump gave Iran a 60-day diplomatic off-ramp. They chose escalation.

A nuclear Iran is exactly what China, Russia, and North Korea want. It advances their shared anti-American agenda and pushes the world toward conflict.

President Trump has been clear: Iran must NEVER have nuclear weapons. He’s backed that stance with strength, restraint, and strategic clarity.

His administration has prioritized peace while posturing our forces to defend American lives. He’s earned the trust of our troops and the American people—and he’s consistently put America first.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
I was pleased today to officially announce the presidential approval of the Colombia Solidarity Bridge expansion—a major victory for Laredo and for the future of trade between the United States and Mexico.

With this latest permit, Laredo becomes the first region on the U.S.-Mexico border to secure five presidential authorizations for international bridges—an unprecedented achievement that reflects years of planning, advocacy, and collaboration across all levels of government. I want to thank @realDonaldTrump, Senators @tedcruz and @JohnCornyn, and our local partners at @cityoflaredo for their critical support in getting this done.

Laredo is now the #9 largest port globally, fueled by booming U.S.-Mexico trade. We hold more presidential bridge permits than any other border region. The World Trade Bridge is the #1 busiest land port in the U.S., and the Colombia Solidarity Bridge ranks as the #3 busiest land port in the southwest. This new expansion only strengthens our position as a global trade leader.

This is a transformational investment in Laredo’s infrastructure and a clear signal that we’re serious about strengthening our role in international commerce. Last year, we processed more than $300 billion in U.S.-Mexico trade through our port. With this expansion, we’re ready to handle even more.

Laredo has always been where trade drives progress and opportunity reaches across borders. I’m proud this project will keep it that way for the future.

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text:
🧵 Today, on a bipartisan basis, the Senate passed its first piece of major legislation this Congress with my bill -- the GENIUS Act.
 
With GENIUS, the United States is one step closer to becoming the crypto capital of the world. (1/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text: The GENIUS Act establishes the first ever pro-growth regulatory framework for payment stablecoins. This bill will cement US dollar dominance, protect customers, increase demand for US treasuries, and ensure that innovation in the digital asset space is in the hands of the United States of America, not our adversaries. (2/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text: Once the GENIUS Act is law, corporations, small businesses, and individuals will be able to settle payments nearly instantaneously, rather than wait for days or weeks and accrue the fees that go with it. Put simply, stablecoins are a paradigm-shifting development that can bring our payment system into the twenty-first century. (4/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text:
With GENIUS, the value of stablecoins will be pegged to the U.S. dollar and backed 1 to 1 by cash or short-term U.S. treasuries.
 
By combining the dollar’s advantages with the speed and efficiency of blockchain technology, the GENIUS Act facilitates trad-fi’s adoption of crypto and ushers in a new generation in payment processing.
 
The prospect of faster and cheaper payments will have far-reaching implications for our financial system. (3/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text: This legislation establishes procedures for issuing stablecoins, designates clear roles for federal and state regulators, implements standards for consumer protection, and includes strong safeguards to deter illicit activity. (5/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text:
Today was a big win for the United States of America.
I’d like to thank my colleagues for supporting this legislation. Particularly, I’d like to thank @LeaderJohnThune, @SenatorTimScott, @SenLummis, @SenGillibrand, and @Sen_Alsobrooks for helping to get this across the finish line. (7/7)

Name: Hagerty, Bill
text: Projections show that with the passage of GENIUS, stablecoin issuers could become the world’s largest holders of U.S. Treasuries by 2030. Such an outcome would shore up our fiscal resilience and cement the U.S. dollar’s status as the global reserve currency. (6/7)

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Russia’s latest strike on Kyiv was its deadliest this year. Make no mistake—this was not just an attack on Ukraine, but on every freedom-loving nation.

Putin’s war machine runs on oil revenue—fueled by Chinese purchases and a global network of banks, shippers, and insurers willing to look the other way.

That’s why I introduced the Sanctioning Russia Act: to dismantle the financial web keeping this war alive. To cut off the cash. Cripple the machinery. And hold every enabler accountable.

With over 70 House Members already signed on and momentum growing daily, it’s time to act—and time to lead.

Congress must pass this bill and shut down the system that funds Putin’s war.
